WEBVTT

00:01.835 --> 00:03.169
 - I'm taking a hormone therapy 

00:03.236 --> 00:05.005
     to stimulate ovulation.    
   - You're trying for a baby?  

00:05.071 --> 00:06.840
      - Thinking about it.      
      I guess that's on me.     

00:06.906 --> 00:08.742
       Actually, about how      
          I've managed          

00:08.808 --> 00:10.777
        to screw up most        
      of my relationships.      

00:10.844 --> 00:12.679
   - I hear that you proposed   
           a reshuffle          

00:12.746 --> 00:14.080
       in which you report      
      to her instead of me.     

00:14.147 --> 00:15.882
  - You're the one who told me  
     to build a relationship    

00:15.949 --> 00:18.051
     with her, earn capital.    
  - I heard Novak's gone AWOL.  

00:18.118 --> 00:21.154
   I think we should use this   
     as a reason to move him    
        out of Trauma OR.       

00:21.221 --> 00:24.924
  - He's, like, unpredictable.  
      - He is toxic chaos.      

00:24.991 --> 00:28.194
        - Theo, it's okay       
   that you wanted this life.   

00:28.261 --> 00:30.497
      - This is part where      
 you tell me you and Mom are... 

00:30.563 --> 00:31.731
     you're praying for me?     

00:31.798 --> 00:33.133
     - Every patient I see,     

00:33.199 --> 00:35.135
  I think, "Is this the person  
        who stabbed me?"        

00:35.201 --> 00:38.238
      - We're going to make     
     an accountability plan     
      for the painkillers.      

00:38.304 --> 00:39.939
  I just matched with a heart.  

00:40.006 --> 00:42.475
    - It sounds like you got    
    walloped with some pretty   

00:42.542 --> 00:45.078
     intense news yesterday.    
- I want to be here for you now.

00:45.145 --> 00:47.013
   However you need me to be.   

00:56.823 --> 00:58.858
          (tense music)         

00:59.993 --> 01:02.162
         (door sliding)         

01:02.228 --> 01:03.630
       - You ready, Mags?       

01:04.264 --> 01:05.732
           It's time.           

01:13.740 --> 01:15.442
 Your heart is in the building. 

01:15.508 --> 01:17.477
       Prepped and ready.       

01:36.563 --> 01:39.365
 - All systems go, Dr. Leblanc. 

01:39.432 --> 01:41.868
          At the behest         
     of our anesthesiologist    

01:41.935 --> 01:43.636
 whose eyes are on the monitor, 

01:43.703 --> 01:46.072
   I'm gonna ask you to count   
       backwards from 10.       

01:47.474 --> 01:48.775
             - Okay.            

01:50.610 --> 01:53.646
             10, 9,             

01:53.713 --> 01:57.083
             8, 7...            

01:57.584 --> 01:59.819
         (opening theme)        

02:13.666 --> 02:15.502
          - Hi, Amira.          

02:15.568 --> 02:18.805
         No, it's 1963.         

02:18.872 --> 02:19.973
              Yeah.             

02:20.507 --> 02:22.575
     Okay, just put it back     
        when you're done.       

02:22.642 --> 02:24.444
        Okay. Yalla. Bye.       

02:24.944 --> 02:26.980
       It's the spare key       
         security code.         

02:27.046 --> 02:29.616
   I mean, how difficult is it  
     to just know the things    

02:29.682 --> 02:32.152
 that you need to take with you 
   and to take them with you.   

02:33.319 --> 02:34.921
 I sound exactly like my father.

02:34.988 --> 02:36.823
           (chuckling)          
        - Was he strict?        

02:36.890 --> 02:41.127
        - He was more of        
    a spiritual philosopher.    

02:41.194 --> 02:43.396
      My mother was strict.     
   My father would have called  

02:43.463 --> 02:45.899
 Mags' surgery a second chance. 

02:45.965 --> 02:48.268
          - Do you miss         
      that kind of outlook?     

02:48.334 --> 02:52.071
    - I wonder if Mags' heart   
    is in the hospital yet...   

02:52.138 --> 02:54.407
  I know I should focus, but... 

02:55.408 --> 02:56.676
          - Thank you.          

02:56.743 --> 02:58.244
     Do you feel comfortable    

02:58.311 --> 03:00.013
       about your strategy      
       for managing today?      

03:00.079 --> 03:02.215
        - As best I can.        
          Why, do you?          

03:02.282 --> 03:04.184
  - Well, I was thinking about  
    what you said last month    

03:04.250 --> 03:05.585
        about that ordeal       
        in the sinkhole.        

03:05.652 --> 03:09.355
  The trapped man. You told me  
     that jumping in blindly    

03:09.422 --> 03:11.824
   is what you know how to do,  
    even when you shouldn't.    

03:11.891 --> 03:14.427
    - Mags' family is making    
    all the decisions today.    

03:14.494 --> 03:19.065
     Talking to the doctors,    
      I'm just waiting for      
       news above ground.       

03:19.632 --> 03:20.934
           It's, uh...          

03:21.501 --> 03:23.236
It's my father's birthday today.

03:23.303 --> 03:26.472
   1963, the year he was born.  
          - Seriously?          

03:26.539 --> 03:28.541
   - How weird is that, right?  

03:28.608 --> 03:31.377
    Do you do, uh, do you do    
      anything to mark it?      

03:32.145 --> 03:34.347
        - This is, uh...        

03:34.414 --> 03:36.516
    Okay, he loved Snickers.    

03:36.583 --> 03:38.318
 And it's one of the few candies

03:38.384 --> 03:40.286
        that you can get        
      both here and there.      

03:40.353 --> 03:43.790
And usually, Amira and I, but...

03:43.856 --> 03:45.692
     nobody's brought it up     
           this year.           

03:47.427 --> 03:49.696
- My brother died when I was 20.

03:50.330 --> 03:52.665
    Car accident, he was 17.    

03:52.732 --> 03:55.401
          - Oh, Karim.          
          I'm so sorry.         

03:55.468 --> 04:00.640
       - The ways we grief      
   and adapt as we... move on.  

04:02.542 --> 04:04.644
       - Thanks, brother.       

04:05.278 --> 04:06.913
       I'll see you soon.       

04:09.382 --> 04:11.217
      (indistinct chatter)      

04:12.185 --> 04:13.586
             - Mark?            

04:14.420 --> 04:16.723
 Dr. Novak, where have you been?

04:16.789 --> 04:19.993
    - I woke up, made coffee,   
       ran 10k, came here.      

04:20.059 --> 04:22.662
   - You know full well I mean  
      "Where have you been      
     for the last two days?"    

04:22.729 --> 04:25.164
   You've been on the schedule  
     but decidedly not here!    

04:25.231 --> 04:27.233
            (sighing)           
        - My mother died.       

04:28.234 --> 04:30.136
- Oh, I'm so sorry to hear that.

04:30.203 --> 04:32.238
      If you'd let us know,     
  we would have been able to--  

04:32.305 --> 04:33.906
   - She didn't actually die.   
      I just wanted to see      

04:33.973 --> 04:37.043
     if you'd still give me     
    a hard time after hearing   
        that news, and...       

04:37.110 --> 04:38.945
     apparently, you would.     

04:39.612 --> 04:42.382
   - You gonna let Pops go on   
  the rides at Centreville too? 

04:42.448 --> 04:44.517
       I mean, he did come      
     a long way to take you.    

04:44.584 --> 04:47.787
- She's going to make him do it.
     She always gets scared.    

04:47.854 --> 04:50.189
      - Nothing wrong with      
      being afraid, Gracie.     

04:50.256 --> 04:52.125
  Theo, I can do the sunscreen  
          on the ferry.         

04:52.191 --> 04:53.926
       - Why is everything      
        you say a lesson?       

04:53.993 --> 04:56.396
           (chuckling)          
 - Welcome to my childhood, kid.

04:56.462 --> 04:59.132
   - Dr. Hunter, your patient   
  in six is back from imaging.  

04:59.198 --> 05:01.067
       I can relay results      
      if you need a minute.     

05:01.134 --> 05:03.836
      - Ah, no, thank you,      
     Dr. Bergeron. I'm good.    

05:07.073 --> 05:10.710
    Okay, girls, take it easy   
        on Pops, alright?       

05:11.511 --> 05:12.745
          Thanks, Dad.          

05:12.812 --> 05:14.614
          - Have a seat         
      for one second, okay?     

05:14.681 --> 05:15.748
           Uh, Theo...          

05:16.316 --> 05:18.451
       - Forget something?      
        - No, just, uh...       

05:18.518 --> 05:20.987
           Was that...          
   Was that lady your friend?   

05:21.054 --> 05:25.058
    You know, it just seemed    
  like there was, uh, you know, 
      like, she knows you.      

05:25.124 --> 05:26.726
           - No, Dad.           

05:26.793 --> 05:29.729
          I don't know,         
    why would you even think    
      something like that?      

05:29.796 --> 05:32.231
  - Alright, I was just asking. 

05:32.298 --> 05:33.499
              Okay.             
             - Okay.            

05:33.566 --> 05:35.668
 - Alright, girls, we're ready. 

05:38.137 --> 05:40.139
  (indistinct PA announcement)  

05:43.209 --> 05:45.111
     - So sweet of your dad     
          to help out.          

05:45.178 --> 05:48.314
      - Liz, what the hell?     
 - I wanted to meet your family.

05:48.381 --> 05:51.918
        Even undercover.        
    - My head is killing me.    

05:52.485 --> 05:54.020
  You know, he pulled me aside  

05:54.087 --> 05:55.822
       and basically asked      
   if you were my girlfriend.   

05:55.888 --> 05:59.192
 - Wow, impressive dad insight. 

05:59.892 --> 06:02.562
         Okay, so fine.         
I accidentally forced the issue.

06:02.628 --> 06:04.864
        - No, you didn't        
      because I denied it.      

06:04.931 --> 06:06.466
           - You lied?          

06:06.532 --> 06:08.368
      Why, because me being     
      sort of still married     

06:08.434 --> 06:10.503
  makes you a bad pastor's son? 

06:10.570 --> 06:12.271
       - Another sick dog?      

06:12.338 --> 06:15.942
    - This is Esther Danbury.   
  Seriously compromised airway. 

06:16.008 --> 06:18.277
             - Whoa.            
  - Try to stay still, Esther.  

06:18.344 --> 06:21.180
- Where's Judah? Where's Bertie?
        I can't see them.       

06:21.247 --> 06:22.849
  - They're right here, Esther. 
          They're okay.         

06:22.915 --> 06:25.952
     Are you breathing okay?    
    - We were in the ravine,    

06:26.018 --> 06:28.254
      the coyote leaped out     
         of the bushes.         

06:28.321 --> 06:30.156
  - Esther, I need you to save  
      your breath, alright?     

06:30.223 --> 06:31.491
       Two units of O-neg.      
             - Yeah.            

06:31.557 --> 06:35.027
   Heart Rate's 105, RESP rate  
      24, BP's 88 over 58.      

06:35.094 --> 06:37.797
     - Yeah, two grams TXA,     
       start ceftriaxone.       

06:39.899 --> 06:42.769
   - Bertie, is our dog okay?   
     - Might hurt a little.     

06:42.835 --> 06:44.704
        (Esther moaning)        

06:45.405 --> 06:48.241
     Alright, I'm gonna need    
   to secure her airway before  
   I can handle the bleeding.   

06:48.307 --> 06:50.710
      - Bertie was on leash     
  when the coyote lunged at us. 

06:50.777 --> 06:52.278
 Esther threw herself in front. 

06:52.345 --> 06:54.981
 - Okay, our nurse is gonna take
 you to your room, okay, Judas? 

06:55.047 --> 06:57.283
    - Here, Esther needs him.   
             - Okay.            

06:57.350 --> 06:58.384
              Oh...             

06:58.751 --> 07:01.621
   - Theo, get that dog out of  
here, this is an operating room.

07:01.687 --> 07:03.589
   - She needs her dog, June.   

07:03.656 --> 07:05.324
        - Can you tell me       
     what you feel, Esther?     

07:05.391 --> 07:06.626
      - How's church, Jim?      

07:08.995 --> 07:10.630
     - Where have you been?     

07:10.696 --> 07:13.900
   - It's... hard to breathe.   

07:13.966 --> 07:16.335
      - Being able to talk      
    is impressive. But, uh...   

07:16.402 --> 07:18.237
      These kinds of trauma     
   usually create what we call  

07:18.304 --> 07:22.742
      a "difficult airway".     
         Options, June?         

07:22.809 --> 07:24.710
   - First, intubation, but...  

07:24.777 --> 07:26.879
    - You think we're dealing   
     with a tracheal injury?    

07:26.946 --> 07:28.548
    - I'm having a hard time    
      getting a good look.      

07:28.614 --> 07:30.149
          It seems like         
       it's mostly facial,      

07:30.216 --> 07:31.317
        but then she has        
      intra-oral bleeding,      

07:31.384 --> 07:33.386
    some loose teeth tissue,    
            swelling.           

07:33.453 --> 07:35.354
- Blind nasotracheal intubation?

07:35.421 --> 07:37.123
       - Nobody does that       
         anymore, okay?         

07:37.190 --> 07:38.357
    If this is a last resort,   

07:38.424 --> 07:40.293
       then it's gonna be       
       an emergency cric.       

07:40.359 --> 07:42.028
Theo, why is the dog still here?

07:42.094 --> 07:44.564
      - June, Bertie stays.     
      - Are you saying you      

07:44.630 --> 07:49.735
 that you can't get me breathing
  because the parts of my face  
  aren't where they should be?  

07:49.802 --> 07:51.971
 - Esther, Esther, listen to me!

07:52.038 --> 07:54.574
          Look, I know          
      you're scared, okay?      

07:54.640 --> 07:56.375
  But I promise you everything  
      is gonna be alright.      

07:56.442 --> 07:59.712
    - Can you just stay back    
      from her open wounds?     

07:59.779 --> 08:02.782
    - 02 SAT's 86 now guys--    
      - Actually, I forgot.     

08:02.849 --> 08:04.617
         I got us this.         
         - What is that?        

08:04.684 --> 08:06.285
     - A video laryngoscope     
         with a stylet.         

08:06.352 --> 08:08.454
        Means we can see        
    what we're doing, and...    

08:08.521 --> 08:10.189
   muscle through the debris.   
             - What?            

08:10.256 --> 08:12.158
    - Nah, keep the emergency   
       cric, just in case.      

08:12.225 --> 08:14.894
   Call that a double-double.   
    - When did you get this?    

08:14.961 --> 08:17.797
      - 50 mg of etomidate      
        and 70 of sux...        

08:17.864 --> 08:19.599
          I don't know,         
      couple of months ago.     

08:19.665 --> 08:22.101
       Am I supposed to...      
         ask permission?        

08:22.168 --> 08:23.769
      - Well, at least tell     
       someone you did it.      

08:23.836 --> 08:25.838
    - Hi, kiddo, we're going    
      to sedate you, okay?      

08:25.905 --> 08:28.407
   And now we're going to use   
       that very good tool      

08:28.474 --> 08:31.143
        to put a tube in,       
   and then when you wake up,   

08:31.210 --> 08:33.045
    you'll be able to breathe   
     way more easily, okay?     

08:33.112 --> 08:35.181
  - You know these things need  
    special approval, right?    

08:35.248 --> 08:36.682
        Devi doesn't need       
      any more reasons to--     

08:36.749 --> 08:38.050
           - To what?           
    - You know, you could've    

08:38.117 --> 08:40.186
   at least answered my texts   
       the last few days.       

08:40.253 --> 08:42.221
     - Okay then, let's get     
       this kid breathing.      

08:42.288 --> 08:43.856
            Alright.            

08:45.124 --> 08:46.926
      - Okay, on your side.     

08:46.993 --> 08:48.394
           Thank you.           

08:48.461 --> 08:49.795
            Alright.            

08:49.862 --> 08:51.864
      Sorry, tender there?      

08:51.931 --> 08:53.833
            - Uh-huh.           
  - Appendix, bet ya anything.  

08:53.900 --> 08:55.635
   - I lost that one as a kid.  

08:55.701 --> 08:57.637
     This pain's definitely     
          my pancreas.          

08:57.703 --> 08:59.438
   - What makes you say that?   

08:59.505 --> 09:02.174
     - Uh, a few years ago,     
        my immune system        
       declared war on it.      

09:02.241 --> 09:03.776
        I've had chronic        
       pancreatitis since.      

09:03.843 --> 09:06.946
      - My uncle had that.      
 Man was in constant discomfort.

09:07.013 --> 09:09.715
 Of course, he was also a weasel
      who drank a 40 a day.     

09:09.782 --> 09:13.619
     - Except, I wasn't much    
of a drinker before this came on
 and barely at all after either.

09:13.686 --> 09:15.454
          - Your loss!          
           (laughing)           

09:15.521 --> 09:17.990
           (coughing)           
         Hey, hey, hey!         

09:18.057 --> 09:20.026
  Time to wake up, nurse lady.  

09:21.561 --> 09:24.063
      - 100 over 70, Kathy.     

09:24.130 --> 09:25.898
      (indistinct chatter)      

09:25.965 --> 09:27.466
           (coughing)           

09:28.434 --> 09:29.769
    - Okay, this'll be cold.    

09:29.835 --> 09:32.238
         (Paige inhales)        

09:34.874 --> 09:38.110
 This is to rule out gallstones 
          or bleeding.          

09:38.177 --> 09:39.979
            (moaning)           

09:40.046 --> 09:42.181
   Are you on any medication?   

09:42.782 --> 09:44.684
       - Pancrelipase and       
       Rabeprazole daily.       

09:44.750 --> 09:47.920
        Tylenol at home.        
     When it gets like this,    
    I always have to come in.   

09:47.987 --> 09:51.157
 - And... what do we usually do?

09:51.223 --> 09:53.225
        - On a good day,        
      listen to what works,     

09:53.292 --> 09:54.860
but mostly tell me why it won't.

09:54.927 --> 09:56.462
   I'm hoping it's a good day.  

09:56.529 --> 09:58.698
 - I like this one, she's fiery.

09:58.764 --> 10:00.466
     - What are you in for?     

10:00.533 --> 10:02.935
   - Congestive heart failure.  
      - Sorry to hear that.     

10:03.002 --> 10:05.638
          - No, no, no.         
 I'll live to fight another day.

10:05.705 --> 10:07.807
         (Kathy coughs)         
      - I'll start fluids.      

10:07.873 --> 10:11.043
  - Thanks. Um... Tell me what  
      usually works, Paige.     

10:11.110 --> 10:13.245
         - Three rounds         
     of intravenous Toradol,    

10:13.312 --> 10:15.815
   aggressive fluids and cipro  
        to avoid abscess.       

10:15.881 --> 10:17.950
 - High-dose anti-inflammatories
        are controversial       

10:18.017 --> 10:20.019
 when it comes to pancreatitis--
        - I know, but...        

10:20.086 --> 10:22.088
    - I think the best thing    
      that we can do is see     

10:22.154 --> 10:24.156
  how you respond to the fluids 
     and manage pain orally.    

10:24.223 --> 10:26.726
- Won't work. I don't metabolize
         well by mouth!         

10:26.792 --> 10:30.997
  The thing is, you guys always 
   make me sit in agony until   
    my body proves me right.    

10:31.063 --> 10:33.099
     Can we please just skip    
      that step this once?      

10:33.165 --> 10:34.834
    - Look, I get you've been   
      through this before,      

10:34.900 --> 10:36.802
but there's a treatment protocol
     that we need to follow,    

10:36.869 --> 10:40.640
         and IV and seds        
    risk anti-platelet effect   
     or acute kidney injury.    

10:40.706 --> 10:44.710
      - But if I'm willing      
    to take that risk to stop   
     my pain, why can't you?    

10:44.777 --> 10:47.647
      - Yeah, why can't ya?     
  I mean, it's her body, right? 

10:47.713 --> 10:49.348
           - Kathy...           

10:52.118 --> 10:55.855
   - Look, I want to help you,  
     Paige, of course, I do.    

10:55.921 --> 10:58.391
      But... I need to look     
   before jumping in blindly,   

10:58.457 --> 11:01.360
    so we're going to do some   
   blood work first, alright?   

11:05.931 --> 11:07.366
        (elevator dings)        

11:08.234 --> 11:09.935
         That was weird.        

11:10.002 --> 11:11.904
 - Zero boundaries, that woman. 

11:11.971 --> 11:15.241
 Let me try to load her up with 
 diuretics and hope that works. 

11:15.307 --> 11:17.209
   - Uh, no, not Kathy. Paige.  

11:17.276 --> 11:20.112
   I just saw her move easily   
    like she wasn't in pain.    

11:20.179 --> 11:22.114
Do you think she's drug seeking?

11:22.181 --> 11:23.616
      - Asking for NSAIDs?      

11:23.683 --> 11:25.251
           They're not          
     a controlled substance.    

11:25.317 --> 11:26.986
       - I know, but some       
      patients lay a track.     

11:27.053 --> 11:29.889
    - Oh, you know the deal.    
     Hiding is second nature    
       with chronic pain.       

11:29.955 --> 11:32.591
       It's when you need       
     somebody to really know    
     what's going on inside,    

11:32.658 --> 11:34.393
           that's when          
      you gotta work at it.     

11:34.460 --> 11:35.761
            - Huh...            

11:36.662 --> 11:38.264
        - No Mags today?        

11:39.198 --> 11:41.267
    - I, uh, took her shift.    

11:42.368 --> 11:45.237
   - People are saying there's  
  something going on with her.  

11:49.208 --> 11:51.844
     - She's having a heart     
      transplant right now.     

11:51.911 --> 11:54.013
     She's been on the table    
        about four hours,       

11:54.080 --> 11:55.781
      about four more to...     

11:56.348 --> 11:58.718
- I didn't know it was that bad.

11:59.318 --> 12:00.886
        - None of us did.       

12:01.654 --> 12:03.222
        - Is she gonna...       

12:04.824 --> 12:07.526
      Is she gonna be able      
      to come back to work?     

12:07.960 --> 12:11.063
- I think the drugs she's asking
      for are a real risk.      

12:11.130 --> 12:12.498
             Paige.             

12:12.565 --> 12:14.033
            - Maybe.            

12:14.934 --> 12:17.069
     But she's the one alone    
         with the pain.         

12:20.272 --> 12:21.607
        - Dr. Devi, sorry.      

12:21.674 --> 12:23.976
  Uh, I imagine you heard about 
     Trauma OR this morning.    

12:24.043 --> 12:26.011
       I know you've been       
       auditing the logs,       

12:26.078 --> 12:28.447
  so if you have any questions  
         about the fancy        

12:28.514 --> 12:29.648
       piece of equipment       
       Dr. Novak ordered--      

12:29.715 --> 12:31.517
       - Oh, I have a lot       
     of questions for Mark.     

12:31.584 --> 12:33.853
     All of which I'd prefer    
    to ask without a buffer.    

12:33.919 --> 12:36.856
        - Yeah, I, uh...        
          - Dr. Curtis?         

12:36.922 --> 12:38.290
This is Murray, Esther's father.

12:38.357 --> 12:40.593
      - I just saw my son,      
 but they said you could tell me

12:40.659 --> 12:41.927
        what's happening        
        with my daughter.       

12:41.994 --> 12:43.662
       - Yes, we were able      
   to secure Esther's airway.   

12:43.729 --> 12:45.264
    She's gonna need several    
    reconstructive surgeries    

12:45.331 --> 12:47.633
 over the next couple of days-- 
     - Well, can I see her?     

12:47.700 --> 12:49.001
       (dog barks lightly)      
          (June sighs)          

12:49.068 --> 12:51.103
   - You need to be prepared.   
     Her face and her airway    

12:51.170 --> 12:52.738
    were damaged extensively.   

12:52.805 --> 12:54.373
       - Well, she's gonna      
         recover, right?        

12:54.440 --> 12:56.408
         She's starting         
      university soon and--     

12:56.475 --> 12:58.878
         - Functionally,        
     her prognosis is good.     

12:58.944 --> 13:01.247
        But she may have        
    some trouble swallowing,    

13:01.313 --> 13:02.915
         she might need         
       a speech therapist.      

13:02.982 --> 13:05.084
         And they'll be         
      some scaring, but...      

13:06.619 --> 13:10.222
     - This dog, we got him     
    the week their mom left.    

13:10.723 --> 13:15.227
  Anytime one of them was sick  
 or sad, he'd be by their side. 

13:15.294 --> 13:17.863
Like, their pain is his to bear.

13:18.931 --> 13:21.467
  - Well, you can come see her  

13:21.534 --> 13:23.469
    in the ICU, I just, uh...   
         (pager beeping)        

13:24.470 --> 13:26.472
        Sorry, you just,        
     you can't take the dog.    

13:27.573 --> 13:30.042
         (dog whimpers)         
    No, I can't, you can't...   

13:31.544 --> 13:32.812
          (dog groans)          

13:34.413 --> 13:36.415
     I got your page, Bash.     
    - You ever held a living    

13:36.482 --> 13:38.918
   creature before because you  
look completely unnatural, June.

13:38.984 --> 13:40.719
     - Then maybe you should    
     take him since you made    

13:40.786 --> 13:42.688
     such a big deal of him     
       staying in Trauma.       

13:42.755 --> 13:44.790
         - Okay... Geez.        

13:45.224 --> 13:46.959
       - What are you guys      
   even doing here? I told you  

13:47.026 --> 13:48.894
    I'd fill you in if I had    
    any news on her surgery.    

13:48.961 --> 13:52.064
    - We were just discussing   
 that while Mags is in recovery,

13:52.131 --> 13:54.667
     if we split her shift,     
     they won't need to hire    
       a temp replacement.      

13:54.733 --> 13:57.303
        - I already have        
  my hands full trying to keep  
     my job from imploding.     

13:57.369 --> 13:58.737
  - What, June, you won't help? 

13:58.804 --> 14:01.006
     - Did she even ask you     
           to do this?          

14:01.073 --> 14:02.908
           Wait here.           

14:02.975 --> 14:04.310
            - June...           

14:06.679 --> 14:11.483
  - I mean, Mags does work at,  
 like, three times the capacity 
       of a normal person.      

14:11.550 --> 14:13.385
 Are we even gonna make a dent? 

14:14.119 --> 14:16.155
    - She coded on the table.   
             - What?            

14:16.222 --> 14:18.190
        - June, did she--       
- They were able to get her back

14:18.257 --> 14:21.427
     but it's not looking...    
     That's all I could get.    

14:21.493 --> 14:23.429
        - Okay, then I'll       
        find out myself.        

14:23.495 --> 14:24.663
             - Bash!            
     What are you gonna do?     

14:24.730 --> 14:26.599
    - I have to talk to them,   
        maybe I can help!       

14:26.665 --> 14:29.602
      - Hey, hey! You can't     
     just storm into the OR     
        with zero context       

14:29.668 --> 14:32.738
     and distract the people    
   who can actually help her.   

14:36.175 --> 14:37.576
            - Bash...           

14:46.485 --> 14:48.954
wailing)                        

15:07.706 --> 15:09.008
         (Paige weeping)        

15:09.074 --> 15:11.744
       - It's about time!       
   The poor girl's dying here.  

15:12.278 --> 15:13.445
      - Your labs are back.     

15:13.512 --> 15:15.581
   - You're not gonna give me   
      the meds I asked for.     

15:15.648 --> 15:17.650
     - The risk of straining    
    your kidneys is too high.   

15:17.716 --> 15:20.786
 We're managing your pancreatic 
    inflammation with fluids.   

15:20.853 --> 15:23.622
    I know it's not the news    
        you wanted but...       

15:23.689 --> 15:25.424
      - I own a restaurant.     

15:25.491 --> 15:28.060
          And you know,         
 it's my job to taste our food. 

15:28.127 --> 15:30.796
   Fatty foods being the exact  
  thing I'm supposed to avoid.  

15:30.863 --> 15:33.532
 - Well, isn't that a sick joke.
            - Right?            

15:33.599 --> 15:35.467
And usually I just have a taste.

15:35.534 --> 15:37.169
Only last night we were slammed.

15:37.236 --> 15:41.807
 And after close, these 18-hour 
 short ribs were calling to me. 

15:41.874 --> 15:44.009
    - Why won't you help her?   

15:44.076 --> 15:45.945
         - I understand         
      this is frustrating.      

15:46.011 --> 15:48.080
I can give you other suggestions
      for pain management.      

15:48.147 --> 15:50.215
   It's just that we see a lot  
        of people come in       

15:50.282 --> 15:52.451
   with pancreatitis and based  
   on my personal experience--  

15:52.518 --> 15:54.353
    - That's really what it's   
    about, though, isn't it?    

15:54.420 --> 15:57.256
        Your experience.        
   The day that you're having   

15:57.323 --> 15:58.791
   when you walk in the room.   

15:58.857 --> 16:01.827
   - Once, a doctor at another  
         hospital seemed        

16:01.894 --> 16:04.463
so personally offended that none
 of his solutions were working, 

16:04.530 --> 16:06.966
      he suggested I apply      
  for medically assisted death. 

16:07.032 --> 16:09.868
     - Jesus. What is wrong     
        with you people?        

16:09.935 --> 16:13.372
    - At least I know I have    
   a fall-back option in case   
    no one can help me here.    

16:13.439 --> 16:14.873
   - This is your life, Paige.  

16:14.940 --> 16:17.576
   That's not some idle threat  
        to waive around.        

16:21.146 --> 16:26.385
    Someone else will come in   
 and offer you other suggestions
      for pain management.      

16:34.960 --> 16:36.295
       - Heard about your       
         friend Leblanc.        

16:36.362 --> 16:40.432
   - You bought $11,000 worth   
   of unsanctioned equipment.   

16:40.499 --> 16:43.469
    - Life-saving equipment.    
  - "Get you fired" equipment.  

16:43.535 --> 16:45.304
          I'm serious.          
      While you were AWOL,      

16:45.371 --> 16:48.240
 Devi was trying to convince me 
      to help her find ways     
       of moving you out.       

16:48.307 --> 16:50.075
         - Well, did ya?        
              - No!             

16:50.142 --> 16:53.445
  - Short-sighted on your part. 
     It could've been a good    
      career move for you.      

16:53.512 --> 16:55.414
      - Why do you not care     
           about this?          

16:55.481 --> 16:57.116
      - C'mon, what's wrong     
        with these doors?       

16:57.182 --> 16:59.251
   - When we started Trauma OR  
     together, you loved it     

16:59.318 --> 17:01.120
 because building and making up 
       the rules as you go      

17:01.186 --> 17:03.455
   works for you, but actually  
  following them, not so much.  

17:03.522 --> 17:05.691
         - Wow, that is         
   so insightful of you, June.  

17:05.758 --> 17:08.894
  - You know what I don't get?  
   If you don't like your job,  
     why are you still here,    

17:08.961 --> 17:11.830
   when you could just leave?   
    Why are you trying to get   
      Devi to push you out?     

17:11.897 --> 17:13.465
   - Because you won't let me!  

17:13.532 --> 17:16.635
      You keep dragging me      
into conversations like this one

17:16.702 --> 17:21.073
     in which you remind me     
 about important how our working
     relationship is to you.    

17:22.508 --> 17:24.977
             (sighs)            
    I never wanted a partner.   

17:25.044 --> 17:27.179
 - Then why did you recruit me? 

17:27.246 --> 17:29.782
         - That was one         
      of my many mistakes.      

17:32.151 --> 17:34.920
      Okay, I'm pretty sure     
 this counts as harassment now. 

17:34.987 --> 17:37.790
    - Well, we're gonna have    
   this conversations because   
  I'm not just gonna walk away. 

17:37.856 --> 17:42.094
      - Really? You should      
    try it sometimes because    
      it really feels good.     

17:42.161 --> 17:43.896
           - I can't.           

17:43.962 --> 17:46.665
       I'm thinking about       
       having a kid, okay?      

17:46.732 --> 17:50.102
  There. And if I do something  
  that's that crazy by myself,  

17:50.169 --> 17:52.805
   I need to know that my work  
     environment is stable.     

17:52.871 --> 17:55.274
      And I know you don't      
  want me putting my emotional  
        stability on you.       

17:55.340 --> 17:58.811
       - Guilt tripping me      
 because you're suddenly nesting
    is the opposite of that.    

17:58.877 --> 18:01.013
 - It's not why I'm saying this.

18:01.080 --> 18:03.148
      I actually like being     
          your partner.         

18:03.215 --> 18:05.350
  And I know you like it, too.  
     Like, you would miss it    

18:05.417 --> 18:09.021
   if you got run out of here   
   for being a stubborn idiot!  

18:09.088 --> 18:10.756
      - Oh, how magnanimous     
          of you, June.         

18:10.823 --> 18:12.958
         - I care about         
   what happens to you, Mark!   

18:13.025 --> 18:15.194
        - The only reason       
     our partnership exists     

18:15.260 --> 18:18.163
 is because you stepped over me 
     to get yourself power.     

18:18.230 --> 18:20.032
        - That happened,        
        like, months ago.       

18:20.099 --> 18:22.801
     - You could've told me     
something instead of burning me!

18:22.868 --> 18:24.603
    - That actually hurt you?   

18:24.670 --> 18:25.904
        (Novak chuckles)        

18:25.971 --> 18:27.873
      That proves my point.     

18:27.940 --> 18:29.141
            You care.           

18:29.208 --> 18:32.444
      - You're too damaged      
      to be a mother, June.     

18:38.851 --> 18:40.719
        - Where's Paige?        

18:41.487 --> 18:42.721
           What the...          

18:44.389 --> 18:45.557
             Kathy?             

18:46.859 --> 18:48.260
           Seriously?           

18:48.327 --> 18:50.262
       - Figured what harm      
     could it do now, right?    

18:50.329 --> 18:52.898
    - But this is a hospital,   
    you're in heart failure,    

18:52.965 --> 18:54.900
  and you have a sick roommate! 

18:54.967 --> 18:57.236
   - Not anymore, Paige left!   

18:57.302 --> 18:59.371
- Left, what do you mean "left"?

18:59.438 --> 19:01.140
       - Well, the details      
     are between me and her,    

19:01.206 --> 19:04.710
  but I will tell you that this 
   place failed her big time!   

19:04.776 --> 19:06.078
   - Do you know where she is?  

19:06.145 --> 19:07.746
        Because she still       
        needs treatment.        

19:07.813 --> 19:10.182
        She needs fluids        
        and pain control.       

19:10.249 --> 19:11.650
 - Is that what these are? Nice!

19:11.717 --> 19:13.685
        - Hey, those are        
       basically morphine!      

19:13.752 --> 19:16.855
        - Oh! Beautiful!        
          Anyway, why?          

19:16.922 --> 19:20.058
     Paige already told you     
   that the good stuff doesn't  
        even work on her.       

19:20.125 --> 19:22.928
 - Those were not meant for you!

19:22.995 --> 19:28.834
 - Well, screw me for wanting to
 feel good, you uncaring bitch! 

19:29.434 --> 19:31.737
        (Kathy coughing)        

19:39.711 --> 19:41.380
     - Where have you been?     

19:41.446 --> 19:45.050
    I mean, you weren't here    
   to stop Paige from leaving.  

19:45.117 --> 19:46.952
         - To go where?         

19:51.156 --> 19:54.726
   - Of course, Abby swore she  
 wanted to go on the drop ride, 

19:54.793 --> 19:58.130
    but as soon as we got to    
the top, she panicked, poor kid.

19:58.197 --> 20:01.600
- Just give it a couple of days,
     she'll remember it like    
        she conquered it.       

20:01.667 --> 20:04.870
     - Uh, hey, do you mind     
           if we sit?           

20:04.937 --> 20:06.405
             - Sure.            

20:07.206 --> 20:11.143
  - Uh, look, I don't want you  

20:11.210 --> 20:14.213
      to feel like you need     
      to hide from me, son.     

20:14.279 --> 20:17.616
 You know, whether you're, well,
   dating that person or not--  

20:17.683 --> 20:18.884
            - Dad...            
          - No, no, no.         

20:18.951 --> 20:21.053
    I should not have pried,    
         that wasn't...         

20:21.119 --> 20:22.688
        Not my business.        

20:22.754 --> 20:24.890
     And to set an example,     

20:24.957 --> 20:30.362
    you should know that I am   
   no longer with the church.   

20:30.996 --> 20:32.531
         - You retired,         
        Dad, that's big--       

20:32.598 --> 20:36.468
   - No, no, no, not retired.   
         Uh... resigned.        

20:38.237 --> 20:41.974
    I wanted to tell you, but   
you're always so busy and, uh...

20:42.040 --> 20:46.044
 - Okay, but... So you and Mom, 
      you still go, right?      

20:46.111 --> 20:50.115
        - Uh, well, yeah,       
 your mother, from time to time.

20:50.182 --> 20:53.118
         But it would be        
        too weird for me.       

20:54.253 --> 20:57.122
          And actually,         
       I work Sundays now.      

20:57.189 --> 20:59.925
        Yeah, for a small       
       landscaping outfit.      

20:59.992 --> 21:01.560
      You know, it's, uh...     

21:01.627 --> 21:06.331
       - Dad, you gave up       
     a lead pastor to, what?    

21:06.398 --> 21:10.168
 Trim hedges? You've been doing 
   that job for 30 years, Dad!  

21:10.235 --> 21:12.938
     - The church has stayed    
        exactly the same.       

21:13.005 --> 21:18.744
    And there are just things   
     about that that I can't    
       reconcile anymore.       

21:19.411 --> 21:21.847
        - You used to say       
    that wrestling with doubt   
        was a good thing.       

21:21.913 --> 21:23.849
             - Yeah.            
      - Right, that, uh...      

21:23.915 --> 21:26.785
   faith grows with the fight.  
       You would say that.      

21:26.852 --> 21:28.287
     - I still believe that.    

21:28.353 --> 21:30.622
     You know what, I also,     
  I sometimes wonder, perhaps,  

21:30.689 --> 21:33.225
  I pushed you too far towards  
   something that I believed.   

21:33.292 --> 21:34.726
         You know, maybe        
      that's why you left.      

21:34.793 --> 21:36.662
   - Oh, so now it's my fault   
    that you're throwing away   

21:36.728 --> 21:38.597
everything we grew up believing?
      Dad, that's unhinged.     

21:38.664 --> 21:40.766
            That's...           
   - It's not, it's not, Theo.  

21:40.832 --> 21:43.135
    No, I think it's so brave   
          what you did.         

21:43.201 --> 21:48.106
       It is. Recognizing       
     that you weren't happy,    
  and then changing your life.  

21:48.173 --> 21:50.375
   The path that you were on.   

21:50.442 --> 21:52.978
     No. Look, if anything,     
        that inspired me.       

21:53.045 --> 21:54.446
             - Oh...            

21:55.213 --> 21:59.685
   Do not rethink your calling  
     because of me, please.     

22:13.699 --> 22:14.866
             - Hey.             

22:15.267 --> 22:16.702
         Still no news.         

22:17.102 --> 22:18.370
         How you doing?         

22:18.904 --> 22:20.572
      - Don't really know.      

22:24.176 --> 22:27.546
     - Think I was a little     
         harsh earlier.         

22:28.046 --> 22:31.216
       Just don't know how      
   to deal with these things.   

22:32.284 --> 22:34.119
     - You're asking me how?    

22:35.220 --> 22:36.988
      I was gonna go pray.      

22:37.055 --> 22:38.757
- Does that really work for you?

22:39.324 --> 22:40.592
            - Uh-huh.           

22:41.893 --> 22:44.763
      Also, it just gets me     
         out of my head,        

22:44.830 --> 22:46.565
          so I don't do         
        something like...       

22:46.631 --> 22:48.700
 - Barge into an operating room.

22:48.767 --> 22:50.068
            - Yeah...           

22:50.602 --> 22:52.637
      Look, if Mags, uh...      

22:56.174 --> 22:58.810
     If she doesn't make it,    
            I just...           

22:59.845 --> 23:02.047
 I think that's it for me, June.

23:03.582 --> 23:05.250
       - What do you mean?      

23:05.784 --> 23:07.119
             - No...            

23:07.185 --> 23:09.221
            Not that.           

23:09.287 --> 23:10.956
            I just...           

23:14.726 --> 23:18.330
     I just know I won't be     
       able to start over.      

23:19.164 --> 23:21.166
         No, not again.         

23:27.272 --> 23:29.474
laying)                         

23:46.324 --> 23:47.759
        (birds chirping)        

23:54.966 --> 23:56.568
        (pills rattling)        

24:16.988 --> 24:19.357
           (in French)          

24:25.030 --> 24:26.398
       - How do you feel?       

24:27.299 --> 24:29.634
        - I was dreaming        
      about the anesthetic.     

24:29.701 --> 24:31.770
     That sleep is so heavy.    

24:31.837 --> 24:35.474
    Every time I wake up now,   
  I feel a huge wave of relief  

24:35.540 --> 24:39.411
 washing over me when I realize 
 how lucky I am to have made it.

24:40.512 --> 24:42.547
  - I'm making vegetable soup.  

24:42.614 --> 24:45.217
  Think you'll be hungry later? 

24:45.717 --> 24:47.452
            - Maybe.            

24:51.623 --> 24:53.258
            Hey, Dad.           

24:58.129 --> 24:59.931
           (in French)          

25:03.435 --> 25:05.437
         (music playing)        

25:06.004 --> 25:07.572
           - Who died?          

25:18.717 --> 25:19.851
          - Hi, Paige.          

25:19.918 --> 25:22.621
       It's Dr. Hamed from      
      York Memorial, again.     

25:22.687 --> 25:25.790
      You haven't returned      
      any of my calls so...     

25:25.857 --> 25:28.126
          just checking         
      if everything's okay.     

25:29.461 --> 25:30.862
       - You're on my bed.      

25:30.929 --> 25:33.865
      - Yeah, you asked me      
      to lie here earlier.      

25:33.932 --> 25:35.934
            - I did?            
             - Hmm.             

25:37.002 --> 25:40.305
   - These immunosuppressants   
       are messing me up.       

25:40.372 --> 25:42.674
      I feel so spaced out.     

25:43.742 --> 25:46.478
       And is that a rash?      
          I feel itchy.         

25:47.212 --> 25:51.182
   - No, I don't see anything,  
  but let's keep an eye on it.  

25:52.551 --> 25:54.219
   - Who were you talking to?   

25:54.286 --> 25:56.855
         - Uh, a patient        
       with pancreatitis.       

25:56.922 --> 26:01.126
  She left AMA and things ended 
    sort of weird between us.   

26:01.192 --> 26:03.828
        - Mmm, maybe she        
        just needs space.       

26:03.895 --> 26:07.198
    - What if she needs help?   
         - She can ask.         

26:07.265 --> 26:09.367
      You know, it's gotta      
         come from her.         

26:11.469 --> 26:13.038
            (sighing)           

26:13.104 --> 26:15.874
      I wish I didn't need      
       all the drugs that       
     they're putting me on.     

26:16.341 --> 26:19.978
   - Hey, look, you and I both  
 know that the immune system... 

26:20.045 --> 26:24.282
   attacks foreign substances.  
  In this case, that's organs.  

26:24.349 --> 26:26.718
     - Will it be the heart     
    that rejects the patient    

26:26.785 --> 26:29.154
         or the patient         
     that rejects the heart?    

26:29.220 --> 26:32.591
     - Both of those options    
        end in rejection.       

26:34.759 --> 26:38.930
   - Because it was never mine  
    to begin with, the heart.   

26:39.397 --> 26:44.035
 And now, part of another human 
   being is braiding with me.   

26:46.471 --> 26:49.040
        Should I be happy       
    that that's all behind me   

26:49.107 --> 26:50.508
  or afraid about what's ahead? 

26:50.575 --> 26:52.177
          - Bash called         
      while you were asleep.    

26:54.980 --> 26:58.750
  - If you want me to tell him  
to lay off a bit, I can do that.

26:58.817 --> 27:00.518
             Gently.            

27:02.954 --> 27:04.456
        How do you feel?        
            (sighing)           

27:04.522 --> 27:07.692
   - I would love it if people  
   would stop asking me that.   

27:09.694 --> 27:11.663
      - Mum's making soup.      

27:12.631 --> 27:15.667
    - Well, if you must know,   
      I feel like a zombie.     

27:15.734 --> 27:18.370
     Like the Walking Dead.     
           (chuckling)          

27:19.037 --> 27:20.872
         - Oh, how long         
      it's been like that?      

27:20.939 --> 27:24.142
   - I think it just came on.   
   - Is it time for your meds?  

27:25.076 --> 27:28.213
 - What if they're not working? 
        - Magalie, don't.       

27:28.279 --> 27:30.649
 Your doctor's checked in every 
    day, he says you're good.   

27:30.715 --> 27:34.586
      - I can feel it, Cam.     
  I can feel it trying to fight 
       its way out of me.       

27:34.653 --> 27:36.655
      - The funny thing is      
       she fought so hard       

27:36.721 --> 27:38.356
  to get into this art school,  

27:38.423 --> 27:40.992
  and now, the thing she likes  
        the most is math.       

27:41.059 --> 27:43.361
           (laughing)           
        - Well, you know,       

27:43.428 --> 27:45.463
      not knowing what path     
 they're on is part of the fun. 

27:45.530 --> 27:47.832
        - This feels like       
       a horrible memory.       

27:48.400 --> 27:51.703
 Being 12 years old and you guys
    were so worried about me.   

27:51.770 --> 27:55.040
           (in French)          

27:55.106 --> 27:57.575
- Never too late to start again.

27:57.642 --> 27:59.544
     - What were you saying     
       about your sister?       

27:59.611 --> 28:03.915
      - Oh, she got invited     
  to the STEM exchange program  
    at this school in England   

28:03.982 --> 28:06.017
   for kids who excel at math,  

28:06.084 --> 28:07.952
       and I can't decide       
     whether to let her go.     

28:08.019 --> 28:10.055
 - Mmm, they all go eventually. 

28:10.555 --> 28:12.657
           Bon appétit.         
         (Magalie gasps)        

28:13.258 --> 28:15.093
     - Something went wrong.    
         We've lost her.        

28:15.160 --> 28:17.028
       (monitors beeping)       

28:19.764 --> 28:21.199
       - You'll never work      
        again after this.       

28:21.966 --> 28:24.202
    - No! There's a bad rash,   
           Dr. Zhang.           

28:24.269 --> 28:25.503
       And her fever won't      
         come down now!         

28:25.570 --> 28:27.272
    - We need to get it out.    

28:27.839 --> 28:29.040
             Please!            

28:29.107 --> 28:30.575
- Magalie, you're only dreaming.

28:30.642 --> 28:32.444
            - Please!           

28:33.712 --> 28:35.213
       You need to get it       
         out of me now!         

28:35.280 --> 28:36.681
         (Magalie gasps)        

28:36.748 --> 28:39.084
        (heavy breathing)       

28:39.150 --> 28:40.985
         (music playing)        

28:42.353 --> 28:44.355
          ♪ Memories ♪          

28:45.757 --> 28:48.693
   ♪ Feel like a disease... ♪♪  

28:50.729 --> 28:52.464
           (knocking)           

28:54.199 --> 28:55.667
           - Come in.           

28:56.501 --> 29:00.171
    - Hey, Cam said you need    
       to be awake anyway.      

29:00.238 --> 29:03.141
        - Yeah, come sit.       

29:04.509 --> 29:06.945
            (sighing)           
           Tell me...           

29:07.746 --> 29:10.014
     What's the panic level     
        out there really?       

29:10.081 --> 29:12.283
             - Um...            
           (chuckling)          

29:12.350 --> 29:15.220
    Well, your mother thinks    
    that her soup will solve    

29:15.286 --> 29:18.656
      all of your problems      
        and I assured her       
       you would be fine.       

29:19.390 --> 29:22.393
   - I love that I don't have   
      to pretend with you.      

29:23.361 --> 29:26.765
         - It does seem         
      like you're adjusting     
    to your meds better now.    

29:26.831 --> 29:31.402
 I know it's been a rocky couple
     of weeks in this place.    

29:31.469 --> 29:32.837
            - Yeah...           

29:35.473 --> 29:37.342
            - Mags--            
          - What is it?         

29:37.408 --> 29:40.645
         I had a thought        
       during your surgery      

29:40.712 --> 29:44.682
   when I got scared that you   
weren't going to come out of it.

29:44.749 --> 29:46.584
 - Every time I fall asleep now,

29:46.651 --> 29:48.686
       I'm afraid I'm not       
         gonna wake up.         

29:50.054 --> 29:52.323
  It's been really unsettling.  

29:52.390 --> 29:55.560
        - That's normal,        
        it'll take time.        

29:56.327 --> 29:57.862
         - What thought?        

29:59.030 --> 30:02.667
       - Look, I know when      
    you and I were together,    

30:02.734 --> 30:04.269
        we had our issues       
         on figuring out        

30:04.335 --> 30:06.037
        how we were going       
         to move forward        

30:06.104 --> 30:08.239
 or if we were going to at all. 

30:08.306 --> 30:12.644
  And I know a lot of that was  
     me and my fears, but...    

30:15.213 --> 30:17.916
      I can't see a future      
      unless you're in it.      

30:19.083 --> 30:22.787
       This is real, Mags.      
     I want this to be real.    

30:35.600 --> 30:39.304
   - Did you... make this when  
   you thought Mags might die?  

30:39.370 --> 30:41.206
             - Um...            

30:41.906 --> 30:44.843
       It was like the day      
         of her surgery,        

30:44.909 --> 30:49.280
      but it's not usually,     
     like, about one thing.     

30:49.347 --> 30:51.216
     It's about everything.     

30:53.117 --> 30:55.520
    - When we were together,    

30:55.587 --> 30:58.957
          I had no idea         
     this was a part of you.    

30:59.824 --> 31:02.961
     - I've never been good     
   at letting people know me.   

31:03.027 --> 31:05.930
 - Not sure that's true anymore.

31:11.336 --> 31:13.238
        (sirens wailing)        

31:32.156 --> 31:34.859
          - Hey, Karim.         
         - Hey, Bashir.         

31:34.926 --> 31:37.228
  I got your call this morning, 
        I was just, uh--        

31:37.295 --> 31:39.063
         - I put it all         
     on the line with Mags.     

31:39.130 --> 31:41.733
    I told her that I want us   
         to be together         

31:41.799 --> 31:44.602
 and she has to think about it. 

31:44.669 --> 31:47.205
  - How's she doing these days? 
        - It's been, uh,        

31:47.272 --> 31:49.674
   it's been a couple of weeks  
       since her surgery.       

31:49.741 --> 31:51.676
       She's moving around      
         the apartment,         

31:51.743 --> 31:54.279
        but there's also        
   the psychological component  

31:54.345 --> 31:56.981
        of when do I get        
    to believe I've survived,   

31:57.048 --> 31:58.917
 and I get that because it's... 

31:58.983 --> 32:00.385
      - Can we go in here?      

32:00.451 --> 32:02.620
        - Uh, yeah, sure.       

32:09.494 --> 32:11.329
       Bashir, do you know      
      what transference is?     

32:11.396 --> 32:15.300
   - Uh, it's when an emotion   
      gets redirected to...     

32:15.366 --> 32:16.868
    where it doesn't belong.    

32:17.635 --> 32:19.537
      You think that's what     
      I'm doing with Mags.      

32:19.604 --> 32:21.306
           - Actually,          
      I'm talking about us.     

32:21.372 --> 32:23.942
 You call or text with thoughts 

32:24.008 --> 32:27.211
 and ask questions like a friend
     or family member would.    

32:27.278 --> 32:28.746
            - Yeah--            
          - Just wait.          

32:28.813 --> 32:31.049
   I'm gonna get through this.  
    I think because you and I   

32:31.115 --> 32:34.686
  are similar in so many ways,  
    culturally, in part, yes,   

32:34.752 --> 32:36.721
 but also just personality-wise,

32:36.788 --> 32:39.857
  that it's been easier for me  
    to let my boundaries lax.   

32:39.924 --> 32:43.061
     And you have this need     
         for a brother,         

32:43.127 --> 32:45.263
        or father figure,       
        or role model...        

32:46.197 --> 32:47.799
    And it pulls at me, man.    

32:48.333 --> 32:50.768
      So as your therapist,     
     I've let my guard down.    

32:50.835 --> 32:53.705
  I also should never have told 
 you about my brother who died. 

32:53.771 --> 32:56.507
             - Bu--             
      - That was about me.      

32:56.574 --> 32:59.010
      And it crossed a line     
  I have never crossed before.  

32:59.077 --> 33:01.112
  Is any of this making sense?  

33:02.480 --> 33:04.449
     - The work we're doing,    
          it's helping.         

33:04.515 --> 33:07.352
      - I know, but I need      
      to keep a firm grasp      

33:07.418 --> 33:09.721
   on professional boundaries.  
            I just...           

33:10.755 --> 33:12.590
    ...can't be your brother.   

33:16.894 --> 33:19.530
       - Are you firing me      
        as your patient?        

33:19.597 --> 33:23.835
       - No, but I do hope      
       that we can reset.       

33:24.502 --> 33:27.438
     So book an appointment     
      and we'll talk then.      

33:39.617 --> 33:41.786
         - Hey, Esther.         
             - Hey!             

33:41.853 --> 33:44.155
     - Your dad hanging in?     

33:44.222 --> 33:46.657
      I don't know, he kind     
      of looked tired or...     

33:46.724 --> 33:50.461
            - Crazy?            
  Yo, he murdered that coyote.  

33:50.528 --> 33:53.664
          - What, why?          
       - Revenge, he said.      

33:53.731 --> 33:56.167
    Like, we don't even know    
     if it was the same one.    

33:56.234 --> 33:58.403
     - Killed it with what?     
       - A hunting rifle.       

33:58.469 --> 34:04.609
 After the attack, he went out, 
   looking every night just...  

34:04.675 --> 34:06.277
        (mimics gunshot)        

34:07.445 --> 34:09.680
     I'm worried about him.     

34:09.747 --> 34:11.282
       - Yeah, I guess so.      

34:11.349 --> 34:15.286
 - And he raised us on his own, 
     that's a lot to carry.     

34:15.353 --> 34:17.055
    And even Bertie's upset.    

34:17.121 --> 34:20.491
    I mean, this is a trauma    
          on all of us.         

34:20.558 --> 34:22.393
    - Look, I checked back in   
         with Plastics,         

34:22.460 --> 34:24.529
    and they said your second   
       surgery went well.       

34:24.595 --> 34:28.232
  - Yeah, I mean, I can swallow 
better, if that's what you mean.

34:28.299 --> 34:31.069
 Do you think after the next one
      though I can go home,     

34:31.135 --> 34:35.039
 maybe help my dad, even make it
     back for Fall semester?    

34:35.106 --> 34:37.275
        - Look, Esther...       

34:39.777 --> 34:42.613
        About a year ago,       
  I was in a helicopter crash.  

34:42.680 --> 34:45.616
  Pilot died and I got stranded 
          in the woods.         

34:46.217 --> 34:49.353
      - Okay? I mean, wow!      

34:49.420 --> 34:51.622
              But--             
  - Why am I telling you this?  

34:52.557 --> 34:54.926
   I know I promised you that   
    everything would be fine.   

34:54.992 --> 34:57.762
 - Are you saying that it's not?
              - No.             

34:57.829 --> 35:00.331
      I'm just saying tha--     
 - Because you seem okay to me. 

35:00.398 --> 35:01.999
        - And am I. I am.       

35:02.066 --> 35:05.470
     And I barely even think    
        about it anymore.       

35:05.937 --> 35:08.339
    But I'm just now starting   
          to understand         

35:08.406 --> 35:09.707
 the effects that it had on me. 

35:09.774 --> 35:13.144
   - I don't really know what   
     to do with any of that.    

35:13.211 --> 35:16.147
            - I know.           
   Which is kind of my point.   

35:16.214 --> 35:20.318
       Okay, how you react      
 to all of this, just trust me, 

35:20.384 --> 35:23.187
  and just try to take it slow. 

35:23.921 --> 35:26.390
 I'm gonna go check on your dad.

35:29.260 --> 35:30.695
     - I need help out here!    

35:30.761 --> 35:32.497
    Need some help down here!   

35:35.032 --> 35:37.301
        (Kathy coughing)        
     - Arnold, what is this?    

35:37.368 --> 35:38.870
       - I just found her       
         collapsed here.        

35:38.936 --> 35:41.105
  Her O2 SAT's brutal, Claire.  
        - This is Kathy,        

35:41.172 --> 35:42.740
   she's been in and out with   
    congestive heart failure.   

35:42.807 --> 35:44.442
   - I heard a tonne of fluid.  

35:44.509 --> 35:46.410
         - Prep trauma.         
             - Yeah!            

35:46.477 --> 35:48.946
         (Kathy moaning)        

35:49.013 --> 35:51.182
           Kathy, hey!          
         Hang in there.         

35:51.249 --> 35:53.784
   Hang in there, we're gonna   
     help you breathe, okay?    

35:53.851 --> 35:56.521
            - No. No!           

35:56.587 --> 35:58.589
          No, not you!          

35:58.656 --> 36:00.558
        (Kathy coughing)        

36:00.625 --> 36:02.660
     - Mr. Danbury, Murray.     

36:02.727 --> 36:06.097
  I know it's been a tough few  
 weeks, but I just wanted to... 

36:06.631 --> 36:08.866
             - What?            
             - Uh...            

36:08.933 --> 36:10.501
       Am I crying blood?       

36:10.968 --> 36:13.171
 - Uh, June. Have you seen this?
             - Yeah?            

36:13.237 --> 36:15.306
   (PA emergency announcement)  

36:15.373 --> 36:17.275
 - I'll get that, you get this. 
          - Yeah, okay.         

36:17.341 --> 36:20.745
            Hi, sir.            
        Just look at me.        

36:21.279 --> 36:23.281
            (sighing)           

36:25.750 --> 36:28.019
       (breathing heavily)      

36:28.085 --> 36:29.554
        (monitor beeping)       

36:29.620 --> 36:31.222
           - Claire...          

36:31.756 --> 36:33.090
             Claire.            

36:33.457 --> 36:34.825
           It's over.           

36:39.997 --> 36:41.666
 - She wouldn't let me tube her.

36:41.732 --> 36:45.603
      By the time help came     
     and got her on the bed,    
    she deteriorated so fast.   

36:45.670 --> 36:47.471
   I did three rounds of CPR.   

36:47.538 --> 36:50.174
  I don't even know how she got 
    here, who brought her in.   

36:50.241 --> 36:51.442
            - I did.            

37:01.586 --> 37:03.988
my street                       
  knew where that thing slept.  

37:04.055 --> 37:06.591
  This city wasn't going to do  
     anything about it so...    

37:06.657 --> 37:09.694
    - But did you physically    
       handle the animal?       

37:09.760 --> 37:11.629
      - After I shot it...      

37:11.696 --> 37:15.166
      I used to go hunting      
     with my uncle, I still     
       have my old rifle.       

37:15.766 --> 37:17.501
 Anyway, I did the right thing. 

37:17.568 --> 37:20.938
    I made sure it was dead,    
        not in any pain.        

37:21.539 --> 37:22.773
              Why?              

37:22.840 --> 37:25.209
- Uh, coyotes can carry bacteria

37:25.276 --> 37:26.677
   that is harmful to humans.   

37:26.744 --> 37:28.546
      - What, like rabies?      

37:28.613 --> 37:30.014
            - Hmm...            

37:30.081 --> 37:31.449
   - Because I've been feeling  
         kind of fluish.        

37:31.515 --> 37:33.017
     - It could be something    
        called tularemia.       

37:33.084 --> 37:34.385
When Esther came in, we gave her

37:34.452 --> 37:35.686
 some precautionary antibiotics,

37:35.753 --> 37:37.555
but if you had it on your hands,

37:37.622 --> 37:39.323
      and then you touched      
           your eye...          

37:39.957 --> 37:42.560
 Okay, so Murray, I'm gonna have
     to cut into the tissue     

37:42.627 --> 37:45.429
  in order to drain the abscess 
   or else you might go blind,  

37:45.496 --> 37:48.866
but, I am gonna numb your first.

37:55.973 --> 37:58.442
     - I know it was stupid.    
        - Just one more.        

37:59.176 --> 38:02.246
 - I just couldn't sleep knowing
 that thing was still out there.

38:02.313 --> 38:03.547
            - Yeah...           

38:04.515 --> 38:06.484
  - I know you think I'm crazy. 

38:09.520 --> 38:13.224
   - Actually, I was wondering  
   if it made you feel better?  

38:14.091 --> 38:16.694
  - I love those kids so much.  

38:17.295 --> 38:19.163
      It's worth the pain.      

38:32.376 --> 38:35.179
      - She texted me after     
        I left that day.        

38:35.946 --> 38:39.150
I invited her to the restaurant,
       cooked her a steak.      

38:39.216 --> 38:40.985
 We've both been feeling lousy. 

38:41.052 --> 38:43.087
         Ended up making        
       friends over that.       

38:43.154 --> 38:44.855
          Sick friends.         

38:45.323 --> 38:48.459
       - I'm sorry, Paige.      
     - You called me a lot.     

38:48.526 --> 38:50.528
 - Yeah, are you still in pain? 

38:50.594 --> 38:52.530
            (scoffs)            
   We'll get you into a room,   

38:52.596 --> 38:55.266
 I'll give you an IV of Toradol.
  - Now you'll do what I want.  

38:55.333 --> 38:57.735
    Two weeks ago it was such   
  a big risk, but now it's not? 

38:57.802 --> 38:59.570
      - It's still a risk.      
    - Then why did my friend    

38:59.637 --> 39:01.505
 have to die for you to take it?

39:03.741 --> 39:07.078
 - Look, I am the kind of doctor
        that takes risks.       

39:07.144 --> 39:10.815
       It's just that day,      
  I was trying not to overreact 

39:10.881 --> 39:13.217
      to something that was     
      happening in my life.     

39:13.284 --> 39:15.853
    Kathy was right about me    
       making it personal.      

39:16.887 --> 39:18.789
      Let me help you now.      

39:28.866 --> 39:30.234
         - What is this?        

39:30.301 --> 39:32.336
     - Dr. Novak and I have     
         been discussing        

39:32.403 --> 39:35.239
     our working situation,     
       and we've decided--      

39:35.306 --> 39:38.008
        - You've decided.       
       - It's been decided      

39:38.075 --> 39:41.846
that he's gonna be transitioning
        out of Trauma OR        

39:41.912 --> 39:45.015
     and no longer connected    
  to the emergency department.  

39:45.082 --> 39:48.219
  - "Banished". That's the word 
       she's looking for.       

39:48.285 --> 39:52.022
   - We wanted you to hear it,  
officially, from the both of us.

39:52.089 --> 39:53.457
            - Heard.            

39:54.024 --> 39:55.393
             - June?            

39:56.193 --> 39:57.228
              June!             

39:57.995 --> 40:01.031
   Yeah, I guess you're right.  
  I'm a starter, not a stayer.  

40:01.098 --> 40:02.633
       - So you're leaving      
          the hospital?         

40:02.700 --> 40:04.602
        - No, no. I have        
   some friends still upstairs  

40:04.668 --> 40:06.137
        that are willing        
         to slot me in.         

40:06.203 --> 40:07.938
      - Maybe I'd ask what      
    this means for me, but...   

40:08.005 --> 40:09.840
         I wouldn't want        
      to sound too damaged.     

40:09.907 --> 40:12.510
       - Yeah, June, uh...      

40:13.911 --> 40:17.114
     When I said that, look,    
       it wasn't about...       

40:33.631 --> 40:36.100
         - Hey, how was         
   your follow-up appointment?  

40:36.167 --> 40:37.935
   - I'm on my way there now.   
             - Okay.            

40:38.002 --> 40:39.437
          - But Bash...         

40:41.272 --> 40:43.774
   I want it to be real, too.   

40:46.177 --> 40:47.344
            - You do?           

40:55.586 --> 40:57.621
        (dramatic music)        

41:09.400 --> 41:11.936
- Sasha and her mom have already
    been waiting 10 minutes.    

41:12.002 --> 41:14.238
     - Uh, I thought it was     
    in my bag, but it isn't.    

41:14.305 --> 41:16.674
            My math.            
  - Where did you see it last?  

41:16.740 --> 41:18.642
   - I don't know, but I have   
      to study on the way.      

41:18.709 --> 41:23.047
      Mr. Redican said that     
   if we don't pass this test,  
    we can't go on the trip.    

41:23.113 --> 41:24.648
           - Found it!          

41:24.715 --> 41:26.717
       - Oh, my God, Mags,      
       you saved my life.       

41:26.784 --> 41:27.918
           (chuckling)          

41:27.985 --> 41:29.453
      (speaking in Arabic)      

41:29.520 --> 41:30.821
       - Okay, one second!      

41:30.888 --> 41:32.122
 - I'm doing nine to two today. 

41:32.189 --> 41:33.624
        - I'll crossover        
        with you at one.        

41:33.691 --> 41:36.494
   - Yesterday, I stayed until  
  four without hitting a wall.  

41:36.560 --> 41:39.029
 - That's great, just don't push
    yourself too hard, okay?    

41:39.096 --> 41:40.631
        The whole reason        
    I'm covering for you is--   

41:40.698 --> 41:43.000
  - Bash, you're picking me up  
  from rehearsal later, right?  

41:43.067 --> 41:45.069
      - I work until nine.      
          - I'll do it!         

41:45.135 --> 41:46.537
      And then we can grab      
         a late dinner.         

41:46.604 --> 41:48.038
            - Great.            
    - Okay, just not burgers.   

41:48.105 --> 41:50.441
    I can't do burgers ever.    
         - Amira, lunch.        

41:53.210 --> 41:54.211
            (sighing)           

41:54.278 --> 41:56.280
 - That is never not exhausting.

41:56.347 --> 41:59.817
   Mmm, their student exchange  
          trip is in...         

41:59.884 --> 42:01.151
          - Two weeks.          

42:01.218 --> 42:02.453
 She used the word "nerve-cited"

42:02.520 --> 42:04.788
  to describe how she's feeling 
          about living          

42:04.855 --> 42:06.824
     in a foreign continent     
          for a month.          

42:06.891 --> 42:08.659
            You, too?           
             - Um...            

42:08.726 --> 42:10.995
       I can still stop it      
         from happening,        

42:11.061 --> 42:13.964
          it's just...          
if that feeling's more about me,

42:14.031 --> 42:16.867
     then I should probably     
    just stay out of her way.   

42:16.934 --> 42:18.502
    - Makes sense, it's hard.   

42:18.569 --> 42:19.770
             - Mmm.             

42:20.771 --> 42:22.206
     Tell me what you think.    

42:22.273 --> 42:23.707
    - I think she should go.    

42:27.511 --> 42:30.114
 - Are you staying over tonight?
